{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review (G6 — approach soundness). AFFIRM: the chosen mechanism is sound and codebase-aligned — overlay `when` is genuinely a `${{ steps.<id>.outputs.<name> }}` expression (see tests/e2e/fixtures/batch-demo.yaml:37 and overlay_triggers_output schema's dynamic boolean map), so sourcing the `when` dropdown from the workflow's overlay_triggers outputs is the natural fit, not a proxy. IR round-trips batch criteria losslessly (test_editor_batch.py), so a selection-driven editor over that list solves the named problem. The server-side-write boundary (\"editor writes files via the server, not the browser\") carries an explicit positive rationale. One coaching finding below on the author-new-prompt mechanism's atomicity.\n\n- [ ] [G6] Specify the author-new-criterion/prompt save mechanism's ordering/atomicity: the plan asserts the outcome (write `.md` → regen index → reference new id → drift gate stays green) but not the sequence or failure handling. Make explicit that index-regen completes BEFORE the new id is referenced in the step (else the IR references an id the index doesn't yet know), and state what happens on a mid-save failure (partial `.md` written but index not regenerated, or a duplicate-name collision) so the editor doesn't leave the library + IR inconsistent. (location: Acceptance Criteria #3 / \"Create new criterion / prompt\" in What)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782502309999203001,"uuid":"8047b4a5-f808-47f8-b451-1449d93e5356"}